items.synopsis: Brendan Watkins is one of thousands of children of Catholic priests who found their biological parents through DNA testing and social media. His birth wasn't the only secret his father kept.

title.children: Thousands of children of priests are finally finding their biological parents through DNA. But that's not the only secret being uncovered

image.altText: The outline of four women, kept anonymous, superimposed over shattered glass

items.synopsis: The Northern Territory coroner has already unravelled evidence of a system in dire need of reform, but her long-running inquiry into the NT's domestic violence response is far from over, resuming in Darwin on Monday.

title.children: Domestic violence inquiry examining killings of Aboriginal women to resume

image.altText: a young aboriginal superhero standing on rock

items.synopsis: An art exhibition celebrating Indigenous superheroes is set to attract crowds in the Northern Territory. And it all started in 1973.

title.children: It's been 50 years since Indigenous artists created their own superhero. This is the legacy

image.altText: MatildasvFrance (3)

items.synopsis: The Matildas find yet another cult hero, a star mourns the death of a loved one, and Aussie rules crowds go nuts around the country. These are the five quick hits from Australia's epic win over France.

title.children: Five quick hits — Matildas star mourns amid jubilation and the AFL is booed by fans as FIFA turned off

image.altText: Cortnee Vine kicks the winning penalty against France at the Women's World Cup.

title.children: How Cortnee Vine showed nerves of steel to send Matildas through to World Cup semis

image.altText: Image of a man smiling in front of green paddocks.

items.synopsis: In Australia's Top End, Munro Hardy, a modern cattleman, combines traditional ranching with cutting-edge technology. Managing data, targeted nutrition, and carbon mitigation are key focuses for the success of his small cattle station.

title.children: The 'data cowboy' transforming cattle yards in the Northern Territory

items.synopsis: When someone asks you to tell the story of the night the Matildas made history, what will you say?

image.altText: A metal device used in ATM card scam

title.children: US Secret Service tip-off leads to arrest of five foreign nationals over alleged ATM scam

image.altText: A sign prohibiting unmanned aerial vehicles flying over the area is on display near the Kremlin wall.

items.synopsis: Suspected Ukrainian drone strikes in Moscow are increasing with analysts saying mass attacks are likely. But questions remain around what Kyiv hopes to achieve and whether there will even be much impact.

title.children: Drone strikes on Moscow are ramping up with signs a 'truly massive' attack may not be far off

image.altText: A composite image of artist Budjerah and Thelma Plum side-by-side

image.altText: Three post it notes in blue, white and yellow, with questions about sex and puberty written on them in messy handwriting.

title.children: The anonymous question a sex educator hears from kids nearly every day

image.altText: A road winds through blackened trees and flattened buildings.

title.children: Worthless banknotes and spending money while you have it: This is what life is like with 100pc inflation

image.altText: A composite of photos of Abbie smiling

image.altText: A woman wearing a colourful dress and hijab wipes tears from her eyes.

items.synopsis: Khadidja is one of thousands of refugees who fled Sudan after a bloody civil war broke out between the army and a paramilitary group. Now she’s stuck inside one of the worst humanitarian crises on earth.

image.altText: Women walk down a street holding umbrellas.

image.altText: Both the doll and the box for Allan, Ken doll's friend.

image.altText: Opera House illustration

image.altText: The face of a young man, who is holding a vape, is covered in vape smoke

image.altText: Dainty green tree frog with an inflated vocal sac under its chin

image.altText: Noosa coastline fading into the Gold Coast skyline

items.synopsis: How will some of Queensland's most popular coastal regions look with 600,000 extra people, and how can they prepare?

title.children: Will the Gold, Sunshine coasts and Noosa be 'loved to death' as 600,000 people move in?

image.altText: Sam Kerr pumps her right fist as she looks to the crowd after the Matildas defeated France.

image.altText: Mary Fowler, Sam Kerr, Caitlin Foord and Steph Catley of Australia celebrate the team’s victory

image.altText: Scott Brunton with a horse in a stable.
